Short answer
- The API rejects requests and returns an HTTP 429 (Too Many Requests) (or an error response for credit-based limits) with details about the exceeded limit and when it will reset.

What the response looks like (examples from the docs)
- Monthly query limit exceeded (example):
  {
    "success": false,
    "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
    "usage": {
      "current": 101,
      "max": 100,
      "exceeded": true,
      "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
    }
  }
  - Fields: current (usage), max (allowed; -1 = unlimited), exceeded (true/false), reset_at (ISO timestamp when monthly limit resets).

- Per-minute / immediate rate limit (example):
  {
    "error": {
      "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED",
      "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds"
    }
  }
  or
  {
    "success": false,
    "error": "Rate limit exceeded: 60 requests per minute",
    "usage": { "latency_ms": 0 }
  }

- Credit-style query limit error (example):
  {
    "error": {
      "code": "INSUFFICIENT_CREDITS",
      "message": "Need 5000 credits, have 5000"
    }
  }

Rate-limit headers
- Every response includes headers you can inspect:
  X-RateLimit-Limit — max requests/minute
  X-RateLimit-Remaining — remaining requests in current window
  X-RateLimit-Reset — seconds until the window resets (or a timestamp in some responses)

What you should do
- Check the rate-limit headers to know remaining quota and reset time.
- Implement exponential backoff and retry after the reset time.
- Reduce calls by caching responses and batching queries when possible.

In short: requests are blocked once limits are exceeded; the API returns a 429 (or an INSFFICIENT_CREDITS error for monthly/credit limits) with structured info about usage and reset time so clients can back off and retry later.
